*1 BC-8 AD: [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Ars Amatoria]]'' contains earliest known reference to [[Ludus Duodecim Scriptorum]].
*1 BC-8 AD: The Roman [[Game of kings]] is a game of which little is known, and which is more or less contemporary with the ''Latrunculi''.
*c. 43 AD: The [[Stanway Game]] is buried with the [[Druid of Colchester]].&lt;ref&gt;''Games Britannia -  1. Dicing with Destiny'', [[BBC Four]], 1:05am Tuesday 8th December 2009&lt;/ref&gt;
*c. 200 AD: A stone ''[[Go (board game)|Go/Weiqi]]'' board with a 17&amp;times;17 grid from a tomb at [[Wangdu County]] in [[Hebei]], [[China]].&lt;ref&gt;John Fairbairn's [http://gobase.org/history/china.html Go in Ancient China]{{dead link|date=December 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*220-265: [[Backgammon]] enters [[China]] under the name ''t'shu-p'u'' (Source: ''Hun Tsun Sii''){{Citation needed|date=September 2008|reason=Source cannot be identified and checked from that name alone.}}
*c. 400 onwards: [[Tafl games|''Tafl'' games]] played in Northern Europe.&lt;ref&gt;[[#Reference-idMurray1951|Murray 1951]], pp.56, 57.&lt;/ref&gt;
