}}
''...Baby One More Time'' received mostly positive reviews. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[Allmusic]] gave the album four out of five stars,&lt;ref name=allmusic&gt;{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r384763|pure_url=yes}} |title=...Baby One More Time |publisher=Allmusic.com |author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |date= |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; writing that &quot;''Baby One More Time'' has the same blend of infectious, rap-inflected dance-pop and smooth balladry that propelled the [[New Kids on the Block]] and [[Debbie Gibson]].&quot; Erlewine further complimented the quality of the singles, particularly &quot;[[...Baby One More Time (song)|...Baby One More Time&quot;]]&quot;, &quot;[[(You Drive Me) Crazy]]&quot;, &quot;Soda Pop&quot; and &quot;[[From the Bottom of My Broken Heart]]&quot;.&lt;ref name=allmusic/&gt; [[Entertainment Weekly]] gave it a mildly positive review, yet wrote that &quot;Spears sounds remarkably like the Backstreet Boys' kid sister&quot;.&lt;ref name=ew&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,286184,00.html |title=...Baby One More Time: Music Review |work=Entertainment Weekly  |author=Beth Johnson |date= |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album two stars out of five, praising the &quot;beefy hooks&quot; but noting that the &quot;shameless schlock slowies... are pure spam.&quot;&lt;ref name=rs&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/britneyspears/albums/album/106495/review/6067393/baby_one_more_time |title=Britney Spears: ...Baby One More Time |work=Rolling Stone  |author=Barry Walters |year=1999 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Commercial performance==
''...Baby One More Time'' debuted at the top of the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] selling 120,500 units,&lt;ref name=britneyfirstweekstats&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Debuts On Top; 'N Sync At No. 2 | date=January 20, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12040569|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT45JI5|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; knocking off three-week chart-topper [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]]'s ''[[Flesh of My Flesh, Blood of My Blood]]''.&lt;ref name=britneyfirstweekstats/&gt; In its second week, the album was displaced for another two weeks by [[Silkk The Shocker]] and [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]] selling more than 181,594 units during the last sales period, pushing it past the 500,000 mark in four weeks, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]] sales data.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Back On Top | date=February 10, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12063283}}&lt;/ref&gt; In its fourth week, the album landed at number one, with sales soaring to more than 229,300 for the week and more than 804,200 in its first five weeks on the chart.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Still On Top, Offspring Up To No. 2, Cher In Top 10 | date=February 17, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12058414|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT4UvTR|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The following week, the album garnered the top spot of the chart again, giving it a total of four weeks at number one, with sales of more than 197,500, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]] data.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney On Top 'One More Time,' But Lauryn Should Ride Grammy Wave Next Week | date=February 24, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12032375|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT5q892|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Weeks after dropping from the number-one position, the album continued to peak at the top spot, with sales of 167,900, according to SoundScan data release.&lt;ref name=britneyfifthweek&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears 'One More Time' Again | date=March 31, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12039233|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT6D4Sq|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The return to the summit gave Spears a total of five weeks at the top. By then, ''...Baby One More Time'' had sold more than 1.8&amp;nbsp;million copies in its first two months of release.&lt;ref name=britneyfifthweek/&gt; After that, the album held the top spot again for the second consecutive week and giving it a sixth week total at the top position, and having sold more than a total of 3&amp;nbsp;million copies.&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour/&gt; In its 47th week on the [[Billboard 200]] the album held strong, peaking at number-three, just giving the album a total of 10&amp;nbsp;million copies and it was later certified [[RIAA|diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Backstage At The 'Billboard Awards' | date=December 10, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12046646|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT3MQGY|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;...Baby One More Time&quot; has spent a total of 51 weeks on the Billboard 200 chart, after exiting the top-ten.&lt;ref name=britneynewalbum&gt;{{Cite web| author=Wendy Hermanson | title=Britney Spears Readies A Funky New Album | date=January 7, 2000 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12045573|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT6jJ9B|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the US ''Billboard'' 200 chart, the album spent a total of 103 weeks, 19 weeks on the Catalog Albums Chart, and 47 weeks on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/britney-spears/baby-one-more-time/332211 |title=...Baby One More Time Chart History |author=Billboard.com |work=Billboard Magazine  |year=1999}}&lt;/ref&gt;

By the end of the year, ''...Baby One More Time'' had sold 8,358,619 units and became the second best-selling album in the U.S., only behind the [[Backstreet Boys]]' ''[[Millennium (Backstreet Boys album)|Millennium]]'', which sold 9,445,732 copies.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Nielsen SoundScan | title=SoundScan 1999 Year-End Music Industry Report | publisher=Entertainment Wire | url=http://www.backstreet.net/www.cgi?x=show&amp;d=news&amp;i=000106-0859-01&amp;c=0 | date=January 6, 2000 | accessdate=July 13, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iPw8mndU|archivedate=July 20, 2009|deadurl=no}}&lt;/ref&gt; Additionally, it is listed as the 17th-highest-selling album of 2000.{{cn|date=May 2011}} On July 19, 2004, the album was certified 14-times platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].&lt;ref name=&quot;RIAA&quot;/&gt; Also, the album landed at number-three on [[List of BMG Music Club's top selling albums in the United States|BMG Music Club all-time best-sellers list]] with 1.6&amp;nbsp;million units, behind [[Shania Twain]]'s ''[[Come on Over (Shania Twain album)|Come on Over]]'' (1.99&amp;nbsp;million) and the Backstreet Boys' ''[[Backstreet Boys (album)|Backstreet Boys]]'' (1.72&amp;nbsp;million).&lt;ref name=&quot;BMG&quot;/&gt; As of July 2009, the album has sold 10,534,000 copies in the U.S. according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], which does not count albums sold through clubs like the BMG Music Service.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ask Billboard&quot;/&gt; Combined, &quot;...Baby One More Time&quot; has sold over 12,154,000 copies in the U.S.{{#tag:ref|As of January 2010, the album has sold 10,554,000 copies in the U.S. according to Nielsen SoundScan,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|author=Up for DiscussionPost Comment |url=http://www.billboard.com/news/britney-spears-debuts-racy-new-single-3-1004016732.story#/news/britney-spears-debuts-racy-new-single-3-1004016732.story |title=Britney Spears Debuts Racy New Single '3' |work=Billboard  |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=October 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; with additional 1,600,000 sold at BMG Music Clubs.&lt;ref name=&quot;BMG&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| author=Barry David | title=Shania, Backstreet, Britney, Eminem and Janet Top All-Time Sellers | publisher=Music Industry News Network | date=February 18, 2003 | url=http://www.mi2n.com/press.php3?press_nb=47877 | accessdate=July 17, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jW8qIpnZ|archivedate=September 3, 2009|deadurl=no}}&lt;/ref&gt; Nielsen SoundScan does not count albums sold through clubs like the BMG Music Service, which were significantly popular in the 1990s.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ask Billboard&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| author=Keith Caulfield | title=Ask Billboard |work=Billboard magazine | date=January 25, 2008 | url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/search/google/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003702049 | accessdate=July 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;|name=u.s. sales|group=note}} The album also debuted at number one on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]] and spent nine non-consecutive weeks at the top.&lt;ref&gt;Canadian Albums Chart:
* {{Cite web| title=Canadian Albums Chart |work=Billboard magazine | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-albums#/charts/canadian-albums?chartDate=1999-01-30 | date=January 30, 1999 | accessdate=May 8, 2011}}
* {{Cite web| title=Canadian Albums Chart |work=Billboard magazine | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-albums#/charts/canadian-albums?chartDate=1999-03-27 | date=March 27, 1999 | accessdate=May 8, 2011}}
* {{Cite web| title=Canadian Albums Chart |work=Billboard magazine | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-albums#/charts/canadian-albums?chartDate=1999-04-17 | date=April 17, 1999 | accessdate=May 8, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; On December 12, 1999, the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] certified it diamond for sales in excess of 1&amp;nbsp;million units.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Canada|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album}}

The album spent two weeks at number-two on the [[European Top 100 Albums]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} and went on to sell over four million copies within the continent, being certified four-times platinum by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]].{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Europe|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album|certyear=2000}} ''...Baby One More Time'' reached number-two in the [[UK Albums Chart|United Kingdom]],&lt;ref name=&quot;UK charts&quot;/&gt; number-four in [[SNEP|France]]&lt;ref name=&quot;French charts&quot;/&gt; and number-one in [[Media Control Charts|Germany]],{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} and was certified three-times platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]],{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United Kingdom|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album}} double platinum by the [[Syndicat National de l'Édition Phonographique]]{{Certification Cite Ref|region=France|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2001}} and three-times gold by the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry,{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Germany|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album}} denoting shipments to retailers of 900,000 units, 600,000 copies and 750,000 respectively.

Additionally, ''...Baby One More Time'' debuted at number-nine in May 1999 on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]], nine weeks later it peaked at number two, behind the [[Dawson's Creek#Music|''Dawson's Creek'' soundtrack]].&lt;ref name=&quot;ARIA charts&quot;/&gt; The album became the seventh highest-selling of 1999 in the country and was certified four-times platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] the following year after shipping 280,000 copies to retailers.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-albums-1999.htm | title=Australian Annual Chart | author=Australian Recording Industry Association | year=1999 | accessdate=July 13, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iPwC4Tdx|archivedate=July 20, 2009|deadurl=no}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Australia|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album|certyear=2000}} ''...Baby One More Time'' opened at number-three on the [[RIANZ|New Zealand charts]], behind Shania Twain's &quot;Come on Over&quot; and [[The Corrs]]' &quot;[[Talk on Corners]]&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;RIANZ&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| url=http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart.asp | title=New Zealand Music Charts| author=Recording Industry Association of New Zealand | date=May 30, 1999 | accessdate=July 13, 2009| archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5PkfqxTDF | archivedate = June 20, 2007| deadurl=no}} Album Chart#1161&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] certified it three-times platinum.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=New Zealand|title=Baby One More Time|artist=Britney Spears|type=album|id=1212}}

==Promotion==
In early 1998, Spears' did several promotions including the &quot;Hair Zone Mall Tour&quot; was a 1999 shopping mall tour. Spears did small sets in malls and food courts around the US, mostly in larger cities. Her set was around 30&amp;nbsp;minutes, and she had two female dancers with her on the stage. Her label, [[Jive Records]], has said that this tour was created to promote Spears' for her debut album (...Baby One More Time) and prepare for her first major tour. This tour is also known as the [[L'Oreal]] Mall Tour, because it was sponsored by [[L'Oreal]]. Spears made many promotional appearances including talk shows and live performances all around the world to help promote the album. On December 1998, Spears' first showed up on MTV's and the Box's most-requested video charts.&lt;ref name=britneyfirstperformances&gt;{{Cite web| author=Wendy Hermanson | title=Britney Spears: New Teen Queen? | date=December 22, 1998 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12050778|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXSx3oMA|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Spears' also poised numerous media appearances weeks before the release of her debut album, most notably on the [[Ricki Lake (talk show)|Ricki Lake Show]], the &quot;Howie Mandel Show&quot;, and as a presenter at the [[American Music Awards]] on Jan. 11. 1999.&lt;ref name=britneyfirstperformances/&gt; She has also appeared live appearance of MTV's Spring Break and (was replaced by a pre-taped segment), and an appearance on the 100th episode of [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)|Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[All That]]''. In addition, Britney was forced to reschedule appearances on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno (1992 TV series)|The Tonight Show With Jay Leno]]'' and ''Live With Regis And Kathie Lee''.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Sidelined With Bum Knee | date=March 4, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12049598|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXSzFdBa|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Before the [[...Baby One More Time Tour]], Spears' was making guest appearances on a number of television shows, including ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno (1992 TV series)|The Tonight Show With Jay Leno]]'' on April 25, Nickelodeon's 12th Annual Kids Choice Awards on May 1, MTV's ''FANatic'' on May 12, ''Live With Regis &amp; Kathie Lee'' on May 3, and ''[[The Rosie O'Donnell Show]]'' on May 25.&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Ready To Hit The Road | date=April 9, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12032891|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT096Nq|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; She also appeared on German talk show ''[[Wetten, dass..?]]'' and on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' on June 25, 1999, [[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]], [[CD:UK]] &amp; [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] in the United Kingdom, she also visited a Japanese music variety show called [[Hey! Hey! Hey! Music Champ]] in Japan to help promote the album. She also performed at the Festival Bar in Italy. Meanwhile, Spears' also played herself in the season of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television sitcom, ''[[Sabrina, The Teenage Witch]]''.&lt;ref name=britneylateperformances&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears: In Drag And On TV | date=August 4, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12045032|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT18ZsF|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Spears was returning a favor to actress [[Melissa Joan Hart]], who had a cameo in Spears's video for &quot;(You Drive Me) Crazy,&quot; according to People magazine.&lt;ref name=britneylateperformances/&gt; The episode featuring Spears' was aired on September 24, 1999.&lt;ref name=britneylateperformances/&gt; She also performed at the 27th Annual [[American Music Awards]], which will be telecast on Jan. 17.&lt;ref name=britneynewalbum/&gt; Then she performed in the 42nd Annual Grammy Awards, which was televised live on [[CBS]] Feb. 23.&lt;ref name=britneynewalbum/&gt; On late 1999, Spears was equally busy, as she performed on ''[[The Rosie O'Donnell Show]]'' on Sept. 27. On Sept. 28, she visited Carson Daly over at MTV's ''[[Total Request Live]]'' at 3:30&amp;nbsp;p.m. (ET).&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Britney Spears Is All Over TV | date=September 24, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12041209|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT1eIZl|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; She also had a mini [[Disney]] concert titled &quot;Britney Spears &amp; Joey McIntyre In Concert&quot;, Spears and [[Joey McIntyre]] performed live in the taped concert event.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web| author=Craig Rosen | title=Nirvana, Paul McCartney, And Britney Spears In Today's TV Tips | date=October 16, 1999 |publisher=Yahoo! Music News | url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12039519|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iXT2Ecjj|archivedate=July 25, 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Tour===
{{Main|...Baby One More Time Tour}}
In April 1999, it was announced that Spears was scheduled to hit the road in June to kick off her [[...Baby One More Time Tour]], in support of the album.&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour/&gt; Although the tour would be Spears's first time as a headliner, she had an extensive background of live performances.&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour/&gt; Spears had already been opening up shows for teen pop icons [['N Sync]],&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour/&gt; [[Tommy Hilfiger]]'s Tommy Jeans company was sponsoring the tour, and Spears continued to be a model for the company.&lt;ref name=britneyfirsttour/&gt;

==Singles==
&quot;[[...Baby One More Time (song)|...Baby One More Time]]&quot; was the first single of the album, and was released in fall of 1998. The song charted at number one in over 70 countries, including the United States where it peaked at number-one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in January 1999 and topped the chart for two weeks.&lt;ref name=&quot;singles peaks&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| title = Artist Chart History&amp;nbsp;—Britney Spears | work=Billboard | year = 2008 | url = http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.vnuArtistId=290150&amp;model.vnuAlbumId=1091020| accessdate = August 10, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;billboard book&quot;&gt;{{Cite book| last = Bronson | first = Fred| title = The Billboard book of number 1 hits | publisher=Billboard Books | year = 2003 | page = 377 | isbn = 978-0-8230-7677-2}}&lt;/ref&gt; It opened at number-one in the [[UK Singles Chart]] selling over 460,000 copies in its first week, a record for a female act at the time,&lt;ref name=&quot;UK Charts&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| author=The Official UK Charts Company | title=Fastest-Selling Singles | publisher=Every Hit | url=http://everyhit.com/record4.html | accessdate=June 11, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and became the [[List of best-selling singles by year (UK)|top-selling single of 1999]]&lt;ref name=&quot;occ&quot;&gt;{{Cite web| author=The Official UK Charts Company | title=Top Selling Singles | year=1999 | url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/stats-top_sellers_by_year-singles.php | accessdate=June 11, 2009 | archiveurl=http://classic-web.archive.org/web/20080104013221/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/stats-top_sellers_by_year-singles.php | archivedate=2008-01-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; and became the [[UK Million-Selling Singles|25th most successful song of all time in British chart history]] with over 1.45&amp;nbsp;million units sold.&lt;ref name=&quot;UK Charts&quot;/&gt;

&quot;[[Sometimes (Britney Spears song)|Sometimes]]&quot; was released as the second single from the album. The song went on to peak at number one in Belgium, Netherlands, New Zealand, Spain and the single also peaked inside the top 10 in over 15 countries. The song only peaked at number 21 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] due to it only being released to radio in the United States. The single also became a commercial success due to the music video that Spears shot in [[Malibu, California]] in April 1999.

&quot;[[(You Drive Me) Crazy]]&quot; was officially released as the third single from the album in fall of 1999. ''Crazy'' became an international hit by peaking at number one in three countries and breaking into the top 5 in many European markets including France, UK, Germany, and Norway. The single peaked at a respectively number 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] because the single was released on [[12-inch single|12&quot; single]] instead of the regular CD single. The single was also used to promote the [[(You Drive Me) Crazy|movie of the same name]]; the film's stars, [[Melissa Joan Hart]] &amp; [[Adrian Grenier]] made a cameo appearance in the music video that was made in [[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]].

&quot;[[Born to Make You Happy]]&quot; was the fourth single released in selected European territories. The song became Spears second number one single in the UK and also became her second number one in Ireland. The single was Spears first single to not be released in the United States. The single sold over 3.6&amp;nbsp;million copies worldwide in 2000.

&quot;[[From the Bottom of My Broken Heart]]&quot; was the fifth and final single (fourth in the U.S. and Australia) released from her debut album. Due to her previous single ''Born to Make You Happy'' being released in other international markets which made this single to only be release in other regions including New Zealand and Australia, where the song peaked at number 37. The song peaked in the top 20 in the United States due to high sales of over one million copies.

